    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.14.38"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">38</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        411 West 115th Street
                        New York City
                        October 20, 1929
                    </dateline>
                
                    <salute>My dear friend,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I spent the morning with Jessie Rittenhsouse<sic>Rittenhouse</sic> and Clinton Scollard, and I read your essay on<del/> the Peterson book to them. They said it was <hi rend="underline">magnificent</hi>, and Jessie was thrilled with the last paragraph. This afternoon I was with Raymond Weaver (the most brill<del>a</del><add>i</add>ant young professor of English at Columbia, biographer of Melville, and the friend who has stood back of me from the first): I read him your essay, and he said"<hi rend="underline">that</hi> is a magnificent piece of writing, <hi rend="underline">and I agree with every word of it</hi>." <hi rend="underline">Magnificent</hi> twice in one day!</p>
                    
                <p>Two evenings ago I had dinner with a Mrs. Meyers from Omaha, Neb.&#8212;&#8212; a stunning person. She was cousin of Robert Tansey of St. Louis &#8212;&#8212;he,cronie of Bill Reedy and my beloved <hi rend="caps">T. B. M.</hi>: and it was for Robert Tansey that my best friend of college &#8212;&#8212;Robert Tansey Laughlin<del/><add>&#8212;&#8212;</add> was named. She had heard you talk and admires you <hi rend="underline">immens<del>l</del><add>e</add>ly</hi>; and she was a college mate of Willa Cather. Somehow I get you mixed up with Tom Outland. So I sent this on, to let you know that love goes out to you, and that all my friends rejoice in what you have done for me. I wrote you for six clippings; but if you can get me six more, I shall send you the stamps for them.<hi rend="underline">Please do</hi>. For we are all going to realize what a stunning thing you have done.</p>
                    
                <p>Yesterday Dr. Howe's new anthology came in, and I was overjoyed to find that in it I am between you and Sara. Title: The Literature of America, Quinn, Baugh, Howe, Scribners. Your Hugh Glass is just before my selections. As Raymond said this afternoon (and it was in his room in 1918 that I read your poem with the book turned face down on the table), the pattern gets clearer and clearer.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Affectionately</salute>
                    
                    <signed>T.S. Jones</signed>
                    
                    <note>Thomas S. Jon<unclear>es</unclear></note>
                </closer>
                
                <postscript>
                    <p>A short sequence on Leonardo da Vinci is unfolding, and Raymond said t this afternoon it is on the highest leve<del>r</del><add>l</add> of anything that has come to me:</p>
                        
                        <lg>
                            <l>While he is silent&#8212;&#8212; he alone who sees,</l>
                                <l>Outlined in fire against an unknown world,</l>
                                    <l>The shifting chiaroscuro of the soul.</l>
                        </lg>
                </postscript>
                    
            </div1>
